  "answer": "**No such argument or passage appears in the Falsafa corpus.**\n\nAfter extensive searches for distinctive phrases like \"Smith Say\", \"Adam Smith\" with Say, \"political economy\" with \"legislative\" or \"moral\", \"laws and institutions\" with \"observed\", and related terms across the English translations (including works by Charles Comte and Charles Dunoyer, where Smith and Say are occasionally referenced), along with reading relevant chapters on analytical methods in moral/legislative sciences (e.g., *Traité de Législation, VOL I*, Chapters 2, 4, and Preface), no matching content was found.\n\nSmith and J.-B. Say appear together only once, in Charles Dunoyer's *Nouveau traité d'économie: VOL II*, Chapter 14 (\"IV. Des conditions auxquelles toute industrie peut être libre\"), where Dunoyer critiques their analyses of production factors (e.g., labor, capital, natural agents) from *Wealth of Nations* and *Traité d'économie politique*, but without reference to modeling moral/legislative sciences or observing laws/institutions as facts.[^1]\n\nCharles Comte's *Traité de Législation, VOL I*, Chapter 2 advocates an analytical method for moral/legislative sciences—describing causes, nature, and effects of habits/laws/institutions as observable facts (not inventing systems)—and cites political economy as a related field needing factual analysis of laws.[^2] However, it does not name Smith or Say, nor explicitly model on political economy.\n\nIf this describes a specific text outside the current 38-work corpus (or untranslated/unindexed), it is not available here.",
